1
00:01:12,775 --> 00:01:15,903
<i>[Children Laughing]</i>

2
00:01:15,979 --> 00:01:17,469
[Honking Horn]

3
00:01:17,547 --> 00:01:19,811
- [Tires Screeching]
- <i>[Loud Crash]</i>

4
00:01:19,882 --> 00:01:21,816
[Barks]

5
00:01:23,486 --> 00:01:26,512
[Speaking Korean]

6
00:01:26,589 --> 00:01:28,955
Easy. Are you all right?

7
00:01:29,025 --> 00:01:32,552
I didn't see you till the last second.
You shouldn't play in the road like that.

8
00:01:32,628 --> 00:01:35,222
Wait a minute. I want my bag.

9
00:01:35,298 --> 00:01:38,790
Here. Hold it.
You wanna take that.

10
00:01:40,970 --> 00:01:44,133
I was on my way back to camp,
you know, from an aid station.

11
00:01:44,207 --> 00:01:46,141
Not so fast, kids. Easy.

12
00:01:46,209 --> 00:01:49,610
<i>[Girl Speaking Korean]</i>

13
00:01:49,679 --> 00:01:51,670
[Korean]

14
00:02:01,591 --> 00:02:03,525
Please don't fight.
Okay. Don't fight.

15
00:02:03,593 --> 00:02:06,824
- Please, I hate coming home to a fight.
- [Korean]

16
00:02:06,896 --> 00:02:09,057
I don't suppose anybody
speaks English here, huh?

17
00:02:09,132 --> 00:02:12,033
<i>English? You speak English?</i>

18
00:02:12,101 --> 00:02:14,865
<i>You speak English?</i>
<i>I speak a little Korean...</i>

19
00:02:14,937 --> 00:02:17,667
but just enough
to get my face slapped.

20
00:02:18,908 --> 00:02:21,570
[Groans]
Can I have that bag, please?

21
00:02:21,644 --> 00:02:26,081
<i>The bag. Yeah. That's it.</i>
<i>That's the one. On the floor.</i>
<i>Right. With the red cross.</i>

22
00:02:26,149 --> 00:02:28,344
Thank you.

23
00:02:28,418 --> 00:02:31,080
I'm a doctor.
You know? Doctor?

24
00:02:31,154 --> 00:02:33,054
<i>How can I make you</i>
<i>understand "doctor"?</i>

25
00:02:33,122 --> 00:02:36,250
Maybe if I sent you a bill
or an old magazine.

26
00:02:36,325 --> 00:02:40,227
Here. Look. See?
I'm with the 4077 th.

27
00:02:40,296 --> 00:02:42,526
4077. You know?

28
00:02:42,598 --> 00:02:45,692
American army hospital.
G.I. Joe. You know?

29
00:02:45,768 --> 00:02:47,702
The good guys. Doris Day.

30
00:02:47,770 --> 00:02:51,035
#You smile, a song begins
You speak, and I hear violins #

31
00:02:51,107 --> 00:02:54,042
# It's magic ##

32
00:02:54,110 --> 00:02:56,044
Oh, thank you. Thank you.

33
00:02:56,112 --> 00:03:01,516
No offense, ma'am, but the water
here has enough germs in it
you could sell it by the slice.

34
00:03:01,584 --> 00:03:03,575
[Shouting In Korean]

35
00:03:06,589 --> 00:03:11,458
Please don't holler.
I have an enormous pain in my head.

36
00:03:11,527 --> 00:03:15,088
It's really enormous.
You could sell advertising space on it.

37
00:03:15,164 --> 00:03:19,828
<i>You know? Advertising?</i>
#<i>Halo, everybody, Halo ##</i>

38
00:03:22,472 --> 00:03:26,738
The 4077. It's about 20 miles
south of here in Oijongbu.

39
00:03:26,809 --> 00:03:29,801
Oh<i>. Oijongbu.</i>

40
00:03:29,879 --> 00:03:31,574
Oh<i>. Oijongbu.</i>

41
00:03:31,647 --> 00:03:34,172
- Oijongbu.
- Oijongbu. Oijongbu. You know?

42
00:03:34,250 --> 00:03:36,741
Oijongbu, Korea. Right?

43
00:03:36,819 --> 00:03:41,620
All right. I'm writing to them.
I'm telling them to come
and get me because I'm hurt.

44
00:03:41,691 --> 00:03:45,787
I must be, because I'm a doctor,
and it says right here I'm hurt.

45
00:03:45,862 --> 00:03:50,492
I want somebody to take this note
to the 4077 th in Oijongbu.

46
00:03:50,566 --> 00:03:54,662
- <i>Oijongbu.</i>
- Oijongbu. Fast. As fast as you can go.

47
00:03:54,737 --> 00:03:57,073
Please. Go fast.
Go as fast as you can.

48
00:03:57,073 --> 00:03:59,064
Please. Go fast.
Go as fast as you can.

49
00:03:59,142 --> 00:04:01,474
- Does she know where Oijongbu is?
- <i>Oijongbu?</i>

50
00:04:01,544 --> 00:04:03,569
Oh, great.

51
00:04:05,748 --> 00:04:08,410
Uh-oh.

52
00:04:08,484 --> 00:04:11,817
Uh, we may have
a little problem here, folks.

53
00:04:11,888 --> 00:04:14,220
My head is bleeding.
I'm sweating.

54
00:04:14,290 --> 00:04:16,724
My pulse feels like
it's playing "The Minute Waltz."

55
00:04:16,792 --> 00:04:19,386
Oh. Look at him.
And I thought <i>I</i> was in trouble.

56
00:04:19,462 --> 00:04:22,829
What you may have here is you may
have a seat at a public concussion.

57
00:04:22,899 --> 00:04:25,299
[Korean]

58
00:04:27,770 --> 00:04:30,068
I gotta hold on.
I don't want to lose consciousness.

59
00:04:30,139 --> 00:04:35,577
I have a feeling if I go to
sleep here, I'm gonna wake up
at the family plot in Maine.

60
00:04:35,645 --> 00:04:39,206
People come from all over the state
to look at our tombstones.

61
00:04:39,282 --> 00:04:42,149
The Pierces have been
in Maine since 1680.

62
00:04:42,218 --> 00:04:44,152
Some of them are dead now.

63
00:04:44,220 --> 00:04:47,246
1680! Huh.

64
00:04:47,323 --> 00:04:50,520
We came over early.

65
00:04:50,593 --> 00:04:54,120
Alexander Pierce played piano
in the cocktail lounge on the <i>Mayflower.</i>

66
00:04:54,197 --> 00:04:57,064
<i>But getting back to me,</i>
<i>concussion-wise...</i>

67
00:04:57,133 --> 00:05:01,229
just talking off the top of
my possibly late, great skull...

68
00:05:01,304 --> 00:05:03,295
Oh, thanks.

69
00:05:04,840 --> 00:05:06,808
I have eight bones in my head.

70
00:05:06,876 --> 00:05:10,744
<i>You do too. It's notjust because</i>
<i>I make $400 a month.</i>

71
00:05:10,813 --> 00:05:15,773
But what my problem is now,
mainly, is that one of my bones
may have split two for one.

72
00:05:15,851 --> 00:05:19,651
You'd be getting a check soon
if you had stock in my head.

73
00:05:19,722 --> 00:05:22,589
[Groans]

74
00:05:22,658 --> 00:05:26,890
[Groans]
Believe me, this hurts me
a lot more than it hurts me.

75
00:05:27,997 --> 00:05:30,329
But enough of this technical talk.

76
00:05:30,399 --> 00:05:33,391
Putting it simply, what has happened is
I have suffered a blow...

77
00:05:33,469 --> 00:05:36,336
to my occipital bone right where
it articulates with the parietal.

78
00:05:36,405 --> 00:05:40,364
<i>What that's called is</i>
<i>that's called a contrecoup.</i>

79
00:05:41,377 --> 00:05:43,368
[Groans Softly]

80
00:05:46,882 --> 00:05:52,821
See, what's happened here is
that my brain has sloshed over
to the other side of my skull...

81
00:05:52,888 --> 00:05:55,914
and is right now, even while
I'm talking to you, turning purple.

82
00:05:55,992 --> 00:06:00,224
You may have noticed certain
purple patches of literary
excess in my spoken word.

83
00:06:00,296 --> 00:06:04,130
But don't worry. I'll keep it clean
in front of the children.

84
00:06:04,200 --> 00:06:06,134
Actually, class...

85
00:06:06,202 --> 00:06:09,103
it is a medical fact that there is
no danger of dying...

86
00:06:09,171 --> 00:06:11,435
if you fall asleep
while you have a concussion.

87
00:06:11,507 --> 00:06:13,975
<i>On the other hand, I have</i>
<i>a reason for staying awake...</i>

88
00:06:14,043 --> 00:06:18,343
which is that I'm afraid I'll die if
I fall asleep while I have a concussion.

89
00:06:19,415 --> 00:06:21,883
I'm just gonna keep talking, all right?

90
00:06:23,953 --> 00:06:27,252
I remember at a party once
in college I got sick on beer.

91
00:06:27,323 --> 00:06:29,587
So, what happened was
this football player...

92
00:06:29,659 --> 00:06:31,820
this big football player
came over to me...

93
00:06:31,894 --> 00:06:34,624
this guy named, uh,
Tank O'Melinski...

94
00:06:34,697 --> 00:06:38,428
Big guy. You may remember him.
He was almost made all-American.

95
00:06:40,202 --> 00:06:43,228
Yeah. That's the one.
So, anyway, uh...

96
00:06:43,306 --> 00:06:46,537
Tank came over and he said,
"Hold onto yourself."

97
00:06:46,609 --> 00:06:49,077
He said, "Hang on to reality.
Don't get sick.

98
00:06:49,145 --> 00:06:52,945
If you let yourself go,
you're finished. Just hold on."

99
00:06:53,015 --> 00:06:55,040
I threw up all over his shoes.

100
00:06:56,085 --> 00:06:59,077
Nice guy.
Beat the hell out of me.

101
00:07:00,456 --> 00:07:02,924
Did I tell you that
th-th-the skull has eight bones?

102
00:07:02,992 --> 00:07:06,018
It does, you know.
Have I ever lied to you?

103
00:07:06,095 --> 00:07:09,792
The occipital, the temporal...

104
00:07:09,865 --> 00:07:15,531
uh, the frontal, two temporal, sphenoid,
ethmoid, two parietal.

105
00:07:15,604 --> 00:07:19,506
Why do I have the feeling I'm losing you?
Look, forget about my skull.

106
00:07:19,575 --> 00:07:24,877
Forget about my concussion.
A person needs a concussion like
he needs a hole in the head.

107
00:07:24,947 --> 00:07:29,475
Let's keep it light.
# I'm a Yankee Doodle Dandy #

108
00:07:29,552 --> 00:07:31,782
# <i>Yankee Doodle do or die #</i>

109
00:07:31,921 --> 00:07:34,617
I can't dance. My head hurts.

110
00:07:34,690 --> 00:07:37,250
# I can't dance
My head hurts #

111
00:07:37,326 --> 00:07:40,489
# I can't dance
My head hurts ##

112
00:07:42,231 --> 00:07:44,968
That smells terrific.

113
00:07:45,102 --> 00:07:49,903
You'd laugh if I told you what I have
a taste for right now. You ready?

114
00:07:49,973 --> 00:07:52,874
A small piece of whitefish...

115
00:07:54,511 --> 00:07:59,278
or some herring
in sour cream with onions.

116
00:07:59,349 --> 00:08:01,283
Marinated herring. Mmm.

117
00:08:03,653 --> 00:08:07,589
When I was in medical school
trying to remember how many
bones I have in my head...

118
00:08:07,657 --> 00:08:11,559
I spent an untold number
of hours at the fabulous
Sol and Sol's Delicatessen.

119
00:08:11,628 --> 00:08:14,859
Not the Sol and Sol's on Third Avenue.
The original Sol and Sol's.

120
00:08:14,931 --> 00:08:18,059
They were brothers.
Sol and Sol.

121
00:08:18,135 --> 00:08:21,798
Nobody could ever figure out
why their parents gave them
both the same name.

122
00:08:21,872 --> 00:08:24,807
Anyway, after a day
of cutting up the odd cadaver...

123
00:08:24,875 --> 00:08:28,902
and while the parts and organs
of the body were rattling
around in my head...

124
00:08:28,979 --> 00:08:31,379
I would dissect a whitefish.

125
00:08:31,448 --> 00:08:33,780
You may have your moments
that you hold dear...

126
00:08:33,850 --> 00:08:36,478
my good sir, madam,
ma'am, children, fellow chickens.

127
00:08:36,553 --> 00:08:38,680
Your hearts may flutter
as your flag unfurls.

128
00:08:38,755 --> 00:08:41,280
Your breaths may quicken
to your national anthem...

129
00:08:41,358 --> 00:08:45,795
but for myself, I shall never forget
the ease, the grace, the earnestness...

130
00:08:45,862 --> 00:08:48,490
with which that whitefish
gave itself up to me.

131
00:08:48,565 --> 00:08:51,625
One eye turned chastely
toward its plate.

132
00:08:51,701 --> 00:08:56,900
The other staring unconcerned
at its consumer: Me,
Benjamin Franklin Pierce, M.D.

133
00:08:56,973 --> 00:08:59,305
"Mental Deficient."

134
00:08:59,376 --> 00:09:03,107
As casually...
almost thoughtlessly...

135
00:09:03,180 --> 00:09:06,013
Yes, [Chuckles]
Even wantonly...

136
00:09:06,082 --> 00:09:08,414
I devoured it.

137
00:09:08,485 --> 00:09:10,419
And without a murmur of dissent...

138
00:09:10,487 --> 00:09:13,684
without so much as a whitefish whimper...
it gave itself up to me.

139
00:09:13,757 --> 00:09:19,696
Its very molecules of protein
melding with my own until today.
That whitefish sings to you.

140
00:09:19,763 --> 00:09:22,857
# I'm a Yankee Doodle Herring #

141
00:09:22,933 --> 00:09:25,026
#Yankee Doodle, do or die #

142
00:09:25,101 --> 00:09:27,535
Not bad, huh? You thought
I was gonna be lousy.

143
00:09:27,604 --> 00:09:30,869
#Yankee Doodle went to London
riding on a pony #

144
00:09:30,941 --> 00:09:35,640
# I am that Yankee Doodle
boy-y-y-y-y ##

145
00:09:35,712 --> 00:09:38,203
I always had
certain problems with pitch.

146
00:09:38,281 --> 00:09:40,806
Though it's very hard
when I'm half dead like this.

147
00:09:40,884 --> 00:09:43,079
I'll be much better later
when I'm immortal.

148
00:09:43,153 --> 00:09:46,953
Well, enough about me.
Let's talk about you.
How do you like me so far?

149
00:09:51,261 --> 00:09:54,424
- I wanted to say something. What was it?
- <i>[Man Speaking Korean]</i>

150
00:09:54,497 --> 00:09:56,624
[Korean]

151
00:09:56,700 --> 00:09:59,066
No, I'll think of it.
Don't help me.

152
00:09:59,135 --> 00:10:01,330
Uh, Yankee Doodle,
occipital, whitefish...

153
00:10:01,404 --> 00:10:04,532
Oh. Oh, yeah. I remember.
Sol and Sol's. Yeah.

154
00:10:04,608 --> 00:10:08,544
They had the most fantastic
waitress in there.

155
00:10:08,612 --> 00:10:11,308
I mean fantastic.

156
00:10:11,381 --> 00:10:13,781
Her name was Lefty.

157
00:10:13,850 --> 00:10:16,614
I think she was, uh, Sol's daughter.

158
00:10:16,686 --> 00:10:20,247
Sol's. Not Sol's. I went with her
my last year at medical school.

159
00:10:21,591 --> 00:10:25,049
After she finished work,
I'd sneak her into the dorm.

160
00:10:25,128 --> 00:10:27,323
What a terrific kid.

161
00:10:27,397 --> 00:10:30,093
And talk about
your parts of the body.

162
00:10:30,166 --> 00:10:33,863
This girl was built
like a brick autopsy.

163
00:10:33,937 --> 00:10:36,997
I'm making you crazy, right?

164
00:10:37,073 --> 00:10:39,803
I'll tell you later.
Here comes the wife.

165
00:10:43,747 --> 00:10:46,875
For me?
Oh. It's some moonshine.

166
00:10:46,950 --> 00:10:48,918
Thank you.
That's very generous of you.

167
00:10:48,985 --> 00:10:51,579
I really shouldn't drink it though.
Maybe just a little.

168
00:10:51,655 --> 00:10:53,646
- [Korean]
- [Korean]

169
00:10:55,926 --> 00:10:59,327
[Coughing]
That's, uh, terrific.

170
00:10:59,396 --> 00:11:01,956
Battery acid, right?

171
00:11:02,032 --> 00:11:04,694
- <i>[Children Giggling]</i>
- [Coughing]

172
00:11:06,169 --> 00:11:09,400
Beautiful kids.
I wish I had something for you.

173
00:11:09,472 --> 00:11:12,839
Some "presento" or something.
I don't have a present.

174
00:11:12,909 --> 00:11:15,673
Oh, wait. Maybe I do.
Wait a minute. In my bag.

175
00:11:16,947 --> 00:11:19,973
You're, uh,
brother and sister, right?

176
00:11:20,050 --> 00:11:23,247
I'm an only child. No siblings.

177
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:26,778
I guess after they had me my parents
decided not to "sibble" anymore.

178
00:11:26,856 --> 00:11:29,188
Here we go.

179
00:11:29,259 --> 00:11:31,193
It's not much,
but it's really nothing.

180
00:11:31,261 --> 00:11:33,889
We fool around at the hospital
with these a lot.

181
00:11:37,801 --> 00:11:42,636
Uh-huh. I think you
better blow this up.
I'm not a big fan of fainting.

182
00:11:44,607 --> 00:11:46,871
Just think of it
as a balloon with fingers.

183
00:11:46,943 --> 00:11:49,207
Or an udder
in search of a cow.

184
00:11:49,279 --> 00:11:53,909
That's "udderly" ridiculous.
If they don't come soon
and put a Band-Aid on my memory...

185
00:11:53,984 --> 00:11:55,918
it's gonna all
come spilling out.

186
00:11:55,986 --> 00:11:58,386
<i>Good. That's enough.</i>
<i>Let me have it.</i>

187
00:11:58,455 --> 00:12:01,947
Why do I have the feeling
that my entire life is
knocking on my tongue...

188
00:12:02,025 --> 00:12:04,425
trying to come out
between my teeth?

189
00:12:04,494 --> 00:12:06,428
There we go.

190
00:12:06,496 --> 00:12:09,090
There.
[Chuckling]

191
00:12:11,301 --> 00:12:13,769
<i>[Korean]</i>

192
00:12:13,837 --> 00:12:16,101
Eh? Oh, yeah. Good. Okay.

193
00:12:16,172 --> 00:12:19,801
Go outside and play
where there's plenty
of fresh air and land mines.

194
00:12:19,876 --> 00:12:23,812
We're not taking those
land mines with us when we go,
you know. They're yours.

195
00:12:26,216 --> 00:12:28,878
Kids. Nice.

196
00:12:28,952 --> 00:12:31,113
I had a nice "kidhood."

197
00:12:31,187 --> 00:12:33,553
You knew where you stood
in those days.

198
00:12:33,623 --> 00:12:37,491
Franklin Roosevelt
was always the president.
Joe Louis was always the champ.

199
00:12:37,560 --> 00:12:39,892
And Paul Muni
played everybody.

200
00:12:43,433 --> 00:12:48,666
Eloise McKay. Eighth grade.
You have to understand.
Those were the old days.

201
00:12:48,738 --> 00:12:52,174
We were brought up
to think that girls were
different, and I was young.

202
00:12:52,242 --> 00:12:54,710
I mean, girls were martians.

203
00:12:56,679 --> 00:13:02,584
Eloise McKay let me touch her slip.
She brought it to school in a box...

204
00:13:02,652 --> 00:13:05,382
and I took it behind the science
building and touched it.

205
00:13:05,455 --> 00:13:10,722
That was it. The whole transaction
could have been conducted by mail.

206
00:13:10,794 --> 00:13:14,787
I hope I haven't shocked anyone.
I mean, we're all adults here.

207
00:13:14,864 --> 00:13:18,595
By the way, I'm a doctor,
and I can tell you for certain
that you're pregnant.

208
00:13:18,668 --> 00:13:20,966
And we know what
causes that nowadays too.

209
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:28,067
The smartest doctor
I ever knew was Samuel Sacks,
head of our medical school.

210
00:13:28,144 --> 00:13:32,945
What a terrific guy. I remember
one day a student was talking
to him, and he said...

211
00:13:33,016 --> 00:13:38,511
"Doctor, what would you do
if a patient died just
as he was leaving your office?"

212
00:13:38,588 --> 00:13:44,390
Without missing a beat, Sacks
said, "I'd turn him around so it
would look like he was coming in."

213
00:13:44,461 --> 00:13:47,089
A lovely man.

214
00:13:47,163 --> 00:13:51,998
Do you know who I hated?
Mrs. Tomassino, my geometry teacher.

215
00:13:52,068 --> 00:13:57,301
She terrified me. She stood over me
in the front row with this big yardstick.

216
00:13:57,373 --> 00:14:00,399
I used to look up into her nose.

217
00:14:00,477 --> 00:14:02,411
She had three nostrils.

218
00:14:02,479 --> 00:14:05,937
I guess she thought it was
symmetrical or something.

219
00:14:06,015 --> 00:14:08,381
But she was really nice
if I got something wrong.

220
00:14:08,451 --> 00:14:11,079
She was very helpful.
She'd look down at me and say...

221
00:14:11,154 --> 00:14:13,379
- [Shouts] "You got it wrong!"
- <i>[Dog Barking]</i>

