- <i>[Dog Barking]</i>

223
00:14:14,046 --> 00:14:16,105
- No, that's all right.
- [Barking]

224
00:14:16,182 --> 00:14:19,413
- That's okay.
She's not here now.
- [Barks]

225
00:14:22,021 --> 00:14:24,285
I really didn't need that yelling.

226
00:14:24,357 --> 00:14:27,815
I wish I wasn't standing so close
to me when I said that.

227
00:14:28,861 --> 00:14:31,489
They really ought to
be here by now.

228
00:14:31,564 --> 00:14:34,465
Somebody from the camp.
I'm gonna go wait in the lobby.

229
00:14:34,534 --> 00:14:36,468
Uh, just talk among
yourselves, huh?

230
00:14:42,308 --> 00:14:44,242
Maybe they're never coming.

231
00:14:45,244 --> 00:14:47,974
Maybe this is it for me.

232
00:14:48,047 --> 00:14:50,982
I'm Ronald Colman,
and this is my <i>Lost Hori</i>z<i>on.</i>

233
00:14:52,051 --> 00:14:54,042
And you're Margo.

234
00:14:55,254 --> 00:14:58,382
I guess you never
saw that movie, eh?

235
00:14:58,457 --> 00:15:00,482
You probably never see any.

236
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:04,291
You really ought to, you know.
There have been some great ox movies.

237
00:15:04,363 --> 00:15:07,093
<i>The Ox-Bow Incident...</i>

238
00:15:07,166 --> 00:15:09,134
<i>A Yank at Oxford...</i>

239
00:15:10,403 --> 00:15:12,928
"The Wizard of Ox"?

240
00:15:13,005 --> 00:15:16,031
"Cow Green was My Valley"?
No, that's cheap.

241
00:15:18,711 --> 00:15:21,271
[Groans]

242
00:15:21,347 --> 00:15:23,508
Come on, Radar.

243
00:15:25,718 --> 00:15:27,709
Come on. Somebody.

244
00:15:30,356 --> 00:15:32,290
Anybody.

245
00:15:44,537 --> 00:15:47,005
Nothing. Nobody.
I can't understand it.

246
00:15:47,073 --> 00:15:49,064
Sorry. Here.

247
00:15:51,477 --> 00:15:54,037
I don't wanna get any dirt
on your wall-to-wall dirt.

248
00:15:54,113 --> 00:15:56,911
[Chuckles]
There's a nice bit of chauvinism.

249
00:15:56,983 --> 00:15:59,315
But I always say, there's
no "vinism" like chauvinism.

250
00:15:59,385 --> 00:16:01,683
# Like no "vinism" I know ##

251
00:16:01,754 --> 00:16:03,688
Merman.

252
00:16:03,756 --> 00:16:06,782
Did I tell you I used to have
a practice back in Boston?

253
00:16:06,859 --> 00:16:09,589
Before I came over here
to work for Harry Truman.

254
00:16:09,662 --> 00:16:15,225
The doctor tell you
to stay away from tobacco?
[Laughing]

255
00:16:17,303 --> 00:16:19,237
You know the great thing
about Boston?

256
00:16:19,305 --> 00:16:22,672
It's where all the musicals come to
try out before they go on to Broadway.

257
00:16:22,742 --> 00:16:25,836
- [Korean]
- Yeah. To fix the book. Add a few songs.

258
00:16:25,911 --> 00:16:28,402
Stuff like that. I saw
all the great ones there.

259
00:16:28,481 --> 00:16:31,211
<i>Oklahoma. King and I. South Pacific.</i>

260
00:16:31,284 --> 00:16:33,650
[In A Deep Voice]
# Some enchanted evening #

261
00:16:33,719 --> 00:16:36,187
#You may meet a stranger #

262
00:16:36,255 --> 00:16:39,713
You know what was great about that?
The way he did the ending.

263
00:16:39,792 --> 00:16:44,627
# Once you have found her
never let her go #

264
00:16:44,697 --> 00:16:47,791
# Once you have found her #

265
00:16:47,867 --> 00:16:52,395
# Never let her #

266
00:16:52,471 --> 00:16:56,305
- # Go #
- <i>[Dog Howling]</i>

267
00:16:57,610 --> 00:16:59,544
I think your dog is better.

268
00:16:59,612 --> 00:17:03,912
I didn't just see hits there
though, you know.

269
00:17:03,983 --> 00:17:06,315
Before I left, I saw this real turkey.

270
00:17:06,385 --> 00:17:09,149
A musical<i>. Up Your Love.</i>

271
00:17:09,221 --> 00:17:13,590
I remember the big song
from that show... a ballad.

272
00:17:13,659 --> 00:17:17,117
#You're mine, I'm yours
We're ours #

273
00:17:17,196 --> 00:17:21,792
#Who but you, who but me
could be us better than we ##

274
00:17:21,867 --> 00:17:25,325
It was a real turkey.
Closed at intermission.

275
00:17:25,404 --> 00:17:28,498
I love the theater,
but I never come late.

276
00:17:28,574 --> 00:17:31,338
That's why the doctor is a tramp.

277
00:17:31,410 --> 00:17:33,344
And what's wrong with drama?

278
00:17:33,412 --> 00:17:37,439
Watch this. Watch this.
You're gonna love this one. Watch this.

279
00:17:38,617 --> 00:17:41,415
Laurence Olivier<i>. Richard III.</i>

280
00:17:45,624 --> 00:17:48,650
Now is the winter
of our discontent...

281
00:17:48,728 --> 00:17:51,720
made glorious summer
by this sun of York.

282
00:17:51,797 --> 00:17:54,960
Now that's really good.
Let's hear your dog do that.

283
00:17:55,034 --> 00:17:57,400
Come on. Bring him in. Come on.

284
00:18:00,773 --> 00:18:03,674
<i>[Man Speaking Korean]</i>

285
00:18:03,743 --> 00:18:06,439
<i>Huh? What? Forgive me.</i>
<i>I don't understand what you're saying.</i>

286
00:18:06,512 --> 00:18:09,345
<i>I'm sorry. I didn't know</i>
<i>I was standing in the dining car.</i>

287
00:18:09,415 --> 00:18:11,349
Can I help you?
[Groans]

288
00:18:11,417 --> 00:18:14,147
[Korean]

289
00:18:14,220 --> 00:18:16,154
- [Woman Laughing]
- [Korean]

290
00:18:16,222 --> 00:18:20,181
- What?
- [Korean]

291
00:18:20,259 --> 00:18:23,524
Oh. Thank you. Okay.
Thank you. I don't know why
nobody's here yet.

292
00:18:23,596 --> 00:18:28,829
I'm sorry. Sometimes the war
hots up and the hospital gets
very busy, you know.

293
00:18:28,901 --> 00:18:32,428
Then at other times you could
shoot off a cannon in there.

294
00:18:32,505 --> 00:18:36,236
Of course, when they do that,
then the war hots up all over again.

295
00:18:36,308 --> 00:18:39,675
- [Korean]
- I get the feeling I'm speaking
in ever-diminishing circles...

296
00:18:39,745 --> 00:18:42,305
until I disappear
up my own mouth-hole.

297
00:18:42,381 --> 00:18:45,248
- [Korean]
- Thank you. Oh, this is wonderful.

298
00:18:45,317 --> 00:18:47,581
I'm glad I called ahead
for a reservation.

299
00:18:47,653 --> 00:18:50,178
- [Korean]
- [Korean]

300
00:18:52,591 --> 00:18:55,651
Mmm. Good.

301
00:18:55,728 --> 00:19:01,223
- Aaah. Hot. Spicy.
- [Korean]

302
00:19:03,135 --> 00:19:06,036
Your baby's gonna need
asbestos diapers.

303
00:19:06,105 --> 00:19:08,039
[Huffs]

304
00:19:08,107 --> 00:19:10,041
Pretty soon, huh?

305
00:19:11,143 --> 00:19:13,873
Don't you sometimes wonder
about babies?

306
00:19:13,946 --> 00:19:16,540
I mean, how do they know
what to do in there?

307
00:19:16,615 --> 00:19:20,381
They start out looking like
little, hairless mice, and
they wind up looking like us.

308
00:19:22,521 --> 00:19:24,512
How's it all work?

309
00:19:26,025 --> 00:19:28,459
I've... I've held
a beating heart in my hand.

310
00:19:28,527 --> 00:19:31,189
I've poked into kidneys and
crocheted them together again.

311
00:19:31,263 --> 00:19:34,721
I've pushed air into collapsed lungs
like beat-up old pump organs.

312
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:37,325
I've squeezed and probed
and prodded my way...

313
00:19:37,403 --> 00:19:39,894
through hundreds of miles
of gut and goo...

314
00:19:39,972 --> 00:19:42,167
and I don't know
what makes us live.

315
00:19:42,241 --> 00:19:44,300
I mean, what keeps us in motion?

316
00:19:44,376 --> 00:19:47,470
What keeps the heart beating
without anybody rewinding it?

317
00:19:47,546 --> 00:19:52,540
Why do the cells reproduce
and "re-re-reproduce"
with such gay abandon?

318
00:19:52,618 --> 00:19:55,746
What force brought us
together in such fantastic complexity?

319
00:19:57,890 --> 00:20:00,324
I've seen a lot of bodies...

320
00:20:00,392 --> 00:20:02,485
and they never cease to amaze me.

321
00:20:04,363 --> 00:20:08,356
Did you ever see
Ann Corio or Margie Hart?

322
00:20:09,368 --> 00:20:11,302
Strippers.

323
00:20:11,370 --> 00:20:15,397
For a long time it was a toss-up whether
I'd marry a stripper or a whitefish.

324
00:20:17,009 --> 00:20:19,477
I remember Polly O'Day.

325
00:20:19,545 --> 00:20:23,413
She worked with a parrot.
He didn't help her strip or anything.

326
00:20:23,482 --> 00:20:26,508
While she got undressed,
he stood on the side and talked dirty.

327
00:20:27,686 --> 00:20:30,849
<i>It was an exciting act.</i>
<i>What a body.</i>

328
00:20:30,923 --> 00:20:32,857
She was built great too.

329
00:20:32,925 --> 00:20:35,792
[Korean]

330
00:20:35,861 --> 00:20:38,853
<i>Yeah. But what I don't understand is</i>
<i>how she got that way</i>...

331
00:20:38,931 --> 00:20:40,865
anymore than how we did.

332
00:20:40,933 --> 00:20:44,528
Look at your hand.
It's one of the most incredible
instruments in the universe.

333
00:20:44,603 --> 00:20:47,868
Of all the bones in the body,
one fourth are in the hand.

334
00:20:47,940 --> 00:20:49,908
Forget the hand.
Look at your thumb...

335
00:20:49,975 --> 00:20:53,706
that wondrous mechanism that
separates us from the other animals.

336
00:20:53,779 --> 00:20:57,146
The world-famous opposable thumb,
that amazing device...

337
00:20:57,216 --> 00:21:01,482
that has transported more students
to college than the Boston post road.

338
00:21:01,554 --> 00:21:04,182
Ideal for sucking,
especially as a baby.

339
00:21:04,256 --> 00:21:08,693
And lauded in song and story
as the perfect instrument
for pulling out a plum.

340
00:21:08,761 --> 00:21:12,822
Or, in the case of the Caesars,
for holding it down for
the gladiator to die...

341
00:21:12,898 --> 00:21:17,198
or holding it up, which means
"See you later at the orgy."

342
00:21:17,269 --> 00:21:22,332
My friends, for getting up and down
the pike, in your pie, in your eye...

343
00:21:22,408 --> 00:21:25,639
I give you the thumb.

344
00:21:25,711 --> 00:21:29,670
Have you any idea, Farmer Brown,
of the incredible complexity...

345
00:21:29,748 --> 00:21:31,682
of this piece
of human apparatus?

346
00:21:31,750 --> 00:21:35,709
[Korean]

347
00:21:35,788 --> 00:21:38,723
Of course not. Never having spent
any time at Sol and Sol's...

348
00:21:38,791 --> 00:21:40,884
swilling borscht and jamming
Latin into your brain...

349
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:44,054
while trying to imagine
if Lefty the waitress
is wearing a garter belt...

350
00:21:44,129 --> 00:21:50,068
you have no idea of the balletic
interplay of parts that
make up the human thumb.

351
00:21:51,971 --> 00:21:57,341
The flexor ossis metacarpi pollicis
flexes the metacarpal bone.

352
00:21:57,409 --> 00:22:02,005
That is, draws it inward
over the palm...

353
00:22:02,081 --> 00:22:05,812
thus producing
the movement of opposition...

354
00:22:05,884 --> 00:22:07,875
and the Boy Scout salute.

355
00:22:07,953 --> 00:22:12,356
<i>Because of this</i>
<i>magical engineering, we could do this.</i>

356
00:22:13,659 --> 00:22:15,650
And this.

357
00:22:17,029 --> 00:22:19,930
[Coughing]
And this.

358
00:22:19,999 --> 00:22:24,595
But our greatest triumph comes not
from flexing the metacarpal bone...

359
00:22:24,670 --> 00:22:28,128
and making a fist, which always seems
to be thirsting to be clenched...

360
00:22:28,207 --> 00:22:30,141
No, no, no, no, no.

361
00:22:30,209 --> 00:22:33,007
Our greatest moment
is when we open our hand...

362
00:22:33,078 --> 00:22:36,980
cradling a glass of wine,
cupping a loved one's chin.

363
00:22:37,049 --> 00:22:39,040
And the best...

364
00:22:39,118 --> 00:22:41,052
the most expert of all...

365
00:22:41,120 --> 00:22:44,419
keeping all the objects of our life
in the air at the same time.

366
00:22:44,490 --> 00:22:49,459
My friends, for your
amusement and bemusement,
I give you the human person.

367
00:22:49,593 --> 00:22:54,724
Thumb and fingers flexing
madly, straining to keep aloft
the leaden realities of life...

368
00:22:54,798 --> 00:22:57,289
ignorance, death and madness.

369
00:22:57,367 --> 00:23:01,098
Thus we create for ourselves
the illusion that we have power...

370
00:23:01,171 --> 00:23:05,574
that we are in control,
that we are... loved.

371
00:23:05,642 --> 00:23:08,509
[Korean]

372
00:23:12,549 --> 00:23:16,645
Thank you. For my next trick, I will
attempt to become stiff as a board.

373
00:23:18,488 --> 00:23:23,118
I hate to eat and faint, but I don't know
if I can even make it down to my knees.

374
00:23:23,193 --> 00:23:25,661
<i>[Horn Honking]</i>

375
00:23:25,729 --> 00:23:27,663
That's him. It's gotta be. Radar!

376
00:23:27,731 --> 00:23:29,790
- <i>[Dog Barking]</i>
- Lassie, it's Radar!

377
00:23:29,866 --> 00:23:32,733
I'll be right there. Wait a second.
Give me my stuff, will you?

378
00:23:32,802 --> 00:23:37,068
Wait a minute. Don't...
Wait a minute. My shoes.
Thank you. Thank you.

379
00:23:37,140 --> 00:23:39,040
[Korean]

380
00:23:42,345 --> 00:23:47,180
Thank you.
The love I'll leave with you.

381
00:23:50,353 --> 00:23:52,787
[Korean]

382
00:23:52,856 --> 00:23:55,552
Take care.
Good-bye, Margo.

383
00:23:56,960 --> 00:23:59,019
<i>[Vehicle Departing]</i>

384
00:24:01,431 --> 00:24:05,231
- Anybody home? [Korean]
- <i>[All Speaking Korean]</i>

385
00:24:05,302 --> 00:24:07,429
You get it?
"I have returned to Korea."

386
00:24:07,504 --> 00:24:11,099
I brought you some "presentos."
For vegetables. Very good.

387
00:24:11,174 --> 00:24:13,108
- [Korean]
- You're welcome.

388
00:24:13,176 --> 00:24:16,339
Kids, some comics
and some candy.

389
00:24:16,413 --> 00:24:19,814
Not very good for you.
You better eat the comics
and read the candy.

390
00:24:19,883 --> 00:24:21,817
Sir, some tobacco.

391
00:24:21,885 --> 00:24:25,150
I think you'll find it's a little better
than the manure you've been smoking.

392
00:24:25,221 --> 00:24:27,951
- [Korean]
- Thank you.

393
00:24:28,024 --> 00:24:31,050
Here's my name
and my unit in Korean.

394
00:24:31,127 --> 00:24:34,221
I want you to contact me
when it's time for the baby, okay?

395
00:24:34,297 --> 00:24:36,822
- [Korean]
- Boy, that smells delicious.

396
00:24:36,900 --> 00:24:38,834
What are you cooking?
What is that?

397
00:24:38,902 --> 00:24:41,336
- [Korean]
- Oh, thank you.

398
00:24:41,404 --> 00:24:43,531
That smells so good.

399
00:24:46,009 --> 00:24:48,910
Mmm. Meat.
Where did you get meat?

400
00:24:50,113 --> 00:24:52,047
Wait a minute.
Where's the dog?

401
00:24:52,115 --> 00:24:56,176
- <i>[Dog Barking]</i>
- Oh, it's delicious.

402
00:24:56,252 --> 00:24:58,540
What do you put in it?

